[According to the Hand, Foot and Mouth Disease Situation update number 531 from WHO dated 16 Jan 2018, in their surveillance summary for HFMD in the Western Pacific region, "The number of HFMD cases reported in week 52 of 2017 [week of 29 Dec 2017] was 1312. As of 31 Dec 2017, there have been 358 764 HFMD cases reported in 2017, and this follows seasonal trends of the same period observed between 2010 and 2016 (Figure 2 -- HFMD cases reported weekly by sentinel sites 2010-2017, National Institute of Infectious Diseases, Japan (http://www.wpro.who.int/emerging_diseases/hfmd_biweekly_report_20180116.pdf)

While the seasonal trend is the same, the figure shows the significant increase observed in 2017, similar to the levels seen in 2015 and 2011. 2013 had slightly less activity than 2017. 2012, 2014, and 2016 were low years. Individual cases and outbreaks of hand-foot-mouth disease (HFMD) occur around the world. In countries with temperate climates, such as Japan, cases occur more often in the spring to fall. Studies are underway to determine why these outbreaks occur and why some people have severe disease. Development of treatments and vaccines to help prevent HFMD in the future is also ongoing (see [2] below). - Mod.LK

